50|$|There are two {{recognised}} {{types of}} contract-inducing fraud, namely dolus dans locum in contractui and <b>dolus</b> <b>incidens</b> in contractum. If, {{but for the}} fraud, the contract {{would not have been}} concluded at all, it is dolus dans; if there would still have been a contract, but on different terms, it is <b>dolus</b> <b>incidens.</b> Although this point has not yet been settled, <b>dolus</b> <b>incidens</b> probably gives a right only to damages, not to rescission of the contract; this is likely also to apply to an ‘incidental’ misrepresentation made without fraud.|$|E

